## Description
Icon webfonts can be a great way to add custom icons to your website. Unfortunately, when a theme has an icon webfont included, and you want to replace an icon with a new one, it can be difficult process.  You have to open the webfont, change out the icon, download the font, and then upload it to your site. It would be great to be able to update your icons without having to go through this process.

This is where using SVG files come in handy. SVG might be the best format for icons on a website hands down. These provide scalable, sharp icons and allow customization of their appearance on hover using CSS. Web developers have access to diverse techniques for incorporating SVGs on a page, each carrying its own set of advantages and limitations. My favorite way to use the SVG directly in my CSS as part of the source code. This allows me to swap out any of the icons for a new one without having to deal with an icon font file.

## Code
Before we get into what this all does, and show you an optional way to do this using CSS variables (custom properties), here is a drop-in replacement for the icon utility code included in the Shadows ReadyTheme provided by Miva.

## Logic
This function is similar to using a webfont since we are still applying out icon to the `::before` pseudo-element. The change we make is the SVG is being used as a `mask-image` instead of the value of the `content` property. By using the <a aria-label="This link will open in a new tab/window." href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/mask">`mask` property</a>, we are able to change or transition colors easily depending on the element state, like `:hover`. Instead of linking to the `mask-image` as a resource, like you might a `background-image`, we have converted the SVG into a Data-URI, or Data-URL if you prefer, which saves on HTTP Requests. The biggest factor this address is how fast the page loads. I have opted to create the `data-url` using Base64 Image encoding, but you could always change them to standard URL encoding if you want.

To update or add a new icon, if you don't have a local way to do it, you can use online tools like [this online conversion tool](https://websemantics.uk/tools/image-to-data-uri-converter/) to get the Base64 encoded Data-URI. Once you have that string, just replace the value of `url("")` to the new Data-URI.
